[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:

- The Americas region reported 60.2% of the global newly reported cases and 63.9% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period, maintaining its dominance as the most severely affected region. The USA reported 48.1% (62 369) of the newly confirmed cases in the region, and Brazil reported 30.1% (39 023), Mexico 4.7% (6094), Colombia 3.5% (4586), Argentina 2.7% (3449), Peru 2.4% (3064), and Chile 2.3% (3012).

- The European region reported 8.4% of the global newly reported cases and 4.5% of the newly confirmed deaths globally. Russia reported 36.3% (6537) of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by Kazakhstan 9.1% (1646), Israel 6.6% (1194), Turkey 5.6% (1012), Bulgaria 4.7% (853), the UK 3.6% (650), Ukraine 3.4% (612), Azerbaijan 2.9% (520), Kyrgyzstan 2.7% (488), Uzbekistan 2.7% (487), Bosnia and Herzegovina 2.7% (482), and Romania 2.5% (456).

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 7.1% of the global newly reported cases and 11.4% of global newly reported fatalities. Saudi Arabia reported 18.1% (2779) of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Pakistan 18.0% (2753), Iraq 15.1% (2312), Iran 14.3% (2186), Oman 8.6% (1318), Egypt 6.0% (912), Kuwait 5.5% (836), Bahrain 3.1% (471), and Qatar 3.1% (470).

- The African region reported 7.6% of the global newly reported cases and 3.2% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 74.1% (12 058) of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Cote d'Ivoire 4.4% (714), Nigeria 3.5% (571), Algeria 3.0% (483), and Kenya 2.3 % (379).

- The Western Pacific region reported 1.4% of the global newly reported cases and 3.2% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 69.0% (2037) of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan 12.4% (366), Australia 8.3% (244), Singapore 6.0% (178), South Korea 2.1% (62), and China 1.6% (46).

- The South East Asia region reported 15.4% of the global newly reported cases and 12.3% of global deaths. India reported 86.2% (28 701) of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 8.0% (2666), Indonesia 5.0% (1681), Sri Lanka 0.32% (106), and Nepal 0.21% (82).

Impression: Caution in interpretation of individual country standings as data reflect reporting on Sun 12 Jul 2020 and most likely have weekend artifact. That being said, the overall picture is basically the same. The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis, followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe followed by the Eastern Mediterranean, followed by the Africa region and the Western Pacific representing the lowest daily caseload of all of the regions, but increased over the usual less than 1% representation due to major increased reporting of cases and deaths from the Philippines.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 13 Jul 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the above text. - Mod.MPP]

