[According to the data on the Worldometer website, the total number of reported cases of COVID-19 worldwide is now 13 235 751, with reports of cases by 217 countries and territories worldwide. The global case count rose by 1.5% in the past 24 hours. The USA and Brazil are still the most severely affected countries in terms of cumulative case counts. In the past 24 hours though, the USA reported the most newly confirmed cases (65 488) followed by India (28 179) and Brazil (21 783). It is sobering to tally the total cumulative case counts for the top 5 countries (USA, Brazil, India, Russia, and Peru), and see that they represent over half of the total cases reported globally (55.4%). A global total of 575 525 deaths have been reported, an increase of 4007 deaths in the past 24 hours.

In descending rank order, the USA is number 1 for the number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, followed by India, Brazil, South Africa, Russia, Mexico, Colombia, Peru, Bangladesh, and Argentina. All these countries are currently experiencing major community-based transmission and considered global hot spots. The range in the top 10 daily newly confirmed cases goes from 3099 to 65 488. The number of daily newly confirmed cases is climbing rapidly in the USA. This listing very much reflects the "hot spots" in terms of countries and regions with ongoing high transmission of the SARS-CoV-2 virus. Noteworthy is that Kazakhstan is in the top 20s (number 20), having reported 1646 newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours. Also worthy of note is that 6 out of the top 10 countries for daily reported newly confirmed cases are from the Americas region, consistent with the continued dominance of SAR-CoV-2 activity.

Impression: The SARS-CoV-2 is still actively being transmitted in all regions of the world, and many countries are showing increases in their daily newly confirmed case counts. - Mod.MPP]
